{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619475"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:31:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:31:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16558"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16558"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.52,0.1,0.05,0,0.33]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9249"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74741"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9249"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16558"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60226"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1164"},{"type":"tags","id":"2097"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"3203"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"},{"type":"tags","id":"4886"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7162"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21912"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21915"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74741"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset right-sided weakness and difficulty speaking. She has a medical history of hypertension and atrial fibrillation. Her medications include Amlodipine and Warfarin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears alert but frustrated. Her pulse rate is 88/min and irregular, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. She has expressive aphasia with preserved comprehension. There is right-sided facial droop and weakness of the right arm (power 2/5) with preserved leg strength. She has reduced sensation to light touch and proprioception in the right face and arm. Her plantar responses are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely location of the infarct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left middle cerebral artery inferior division","Left middle cerebral artery stem","Right middle cerebral artery superior division","Right middle cerebral artery inferior division","Left middle cerebral artery superior division"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a classic stroke syndrome involving the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft middle cerebral artery superior division\u003C/strong\u003E. The superior division supplies the frontal and parietal lobes, including the primary motor and sensory cortices for the face and arm, as well as Broca\u0027s area in the frontal lobe. This explains the combination of contralateral (right-sided) face and arm weakness, sensory loss, and expressive (Broca\u0027s) aphasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft middle cerebral artery inferior division\u003C/strong\u003E stroke typically affects the temporal lobe and would cause receptive (Wernicke\u0027s) aphasia and superior quadrantanopia, which are not present here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft middle cerebral artery stem\u003C/strong\u003E occlusion would cause more extensive deficits including the entire MCA territory, typically with both superior and inferior division symptoms including leg weakness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight middle cerebral artery superior division\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eright middle cerebral artery inferior division\u003C/strong\u003E strokes would not cause aphasia as language function is usually lateralised to the left hemisphere in right-handed individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe middle cerebral artery supplies the lateral surface of the brain through its superior and inferior divisions. The superior division supplies the frontal and parietal lobes including primary motor and sensory cortices for face and arm, and Broca\u0027s area (in the left hemisphere). The inferior division supplies the temporal lobe including Wernicke\u0027s area (in the left hemisphere).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Middle cerebral artery (MCA) superior division infarcts typically cause contralateral face and arm weakness with preserved leg function","Broca\u0027s aphasia occurs with left frontal lobe lesions in the MCA superior division territory","Combined motor, sensory and language deficits suggest cortical rather than subcortical involvement"],"references":["Nogles TE, Galuska MA. Middle Cerebral Artery Stroke. 2023 Apr 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32310592.","Cooke J, Maingard J, Chandra RV, Slater LA, Brooks M, Asadi H. Acute middle cerebral artery stroke in a patient with a patent middle cerebral artery. Neurol Clin Pract. 2019 Jun;9(3):250-255. doi: 10.1212/CPJ.0000000000000605. PMID: 31341713; PMCID: PMC6615667.","Walcott BP, Miller JC, Kwon CS, Sheth SA, Hiller M, Cronin CA, Schwamm LH, Simard JM, Kahle KT, Kimberly WT, Sheth KN. Outcomes in severe middle cerebral artery ischemic stroke. Neurocrit Care. 2014 Aug;21(1):20-6. doi: 10.1007/s12028-013-9838-x. PMID: 23839704; PMCID: PMC3880600.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60226"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16558"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60226","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60226"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T18:28:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T18:28:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9249"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74741"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},